09130nam a22012015i 9781501507984DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2019944934  a97815015079847 a10.1515/97815015079842doi  a(DE-B1597)490713  a(OCoLC)1125194554  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aP115b.M735 2019 7aLAN0090002bisacsh00aMultidisciplinary Perspectives on Multilingualism :bThe Fundamentals /ced. by Simona Montanari, Suzanne Quay. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (VII, 422 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLanguage Contact and Bilingualism [LCB] ;v1900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Multilingualism from Multidisciplinary Perspectives: Introduction and Overview -- tPart I: Societal Multilingualism: Historical, Political, Economic and Educational Forces in Different World Regions -- t2. Multilingualism, Language Varieties and Ideology in North Africa -- t3. Multilingualism in Southeast Asia: The Post-Colonial Language Stories of Hong Kong, Malaysia and Singapore -- t4. Multilingualism in Europe -- t5. Multilingualism in North America -- tPart II: Language Use in Multilingual Communities -- t6. Diglossia in Multilingual Communities -- t7. Codeswitching in Multilingual Communities -- t8. Receptive Multilingualism -- t9. Multilingualism in Signing Communities -- tPart III: Individual Multilingualism: From Development to Loss -- t10. Fostering Multilingualism in Childhood -- t11. Family Language Practices in Multilingual Transcultural Families -- t12. Multilingualism through Schooling -- t13. Language Attrition in Multilinguals -- tPart IV: Differences between Bilingualism and Multilingualism -- t14. Facilitated Language Learning in Multilinguals -- t15. Cross-linguistic Interaction and Multilingual Awareness -- t16. Multilingualism and Cognitive Benefits in Aging -- t17. Multilingual Language Processing and the Multilingual Brain -- t18. Conclusion and Directions for Future Research -- tIndex of Key Words -- tIndex of Languages / Language Families -- tIndex of Countries and Continents0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMultilingualism is a typical aspect of everyday life for most of the world’s population; it has existed since the beginning of humanity and among individuals of all backgrounds. Nonetheless, it has often been treated as a variant of bilingualism or as a phenomenon unique to individual areas of study. The purpose of this book is to review current knowledge about the acquisition, use and loss of multiple languages using a multidisciplinary perspective, highlighting the common themes and stimulating insights that can emerge when multilingualism is viewed from different but related areas of investigation. The chapters focus on research evidence, showing that multilingualism is a complex phenomenon that involves a myriad of linguistic and extra-linguistic forces and that should be studied in its own right as evidence of human potential and capacity for language. The book is primarily addressed to students and scholars interested in deepening their understanding of the different facets of multilingualism, including the individual and societal circumstances that contribute to it, the cognitive and neural mechanisms that make it possible, and the dynamics involved in the acquisition, use and loss of multiple languages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aMultilingualism. 4aDrittsprache. 4aMultilingualismus. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aMultilingualism.  aThird language acquisition.1 aAllgäuer-Hackl, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aB